---
  Gasthaus Application Testing Guide

  Phase 0 — Start All Services

  Terminal 1: PostgreSQL + Redis (Docker)
  cd ~/Gasthaus/gasthaus-backend
  docker compose up -d

  Terminal 2: Spring Boot Backend (port 8080)
  cd ~/Gasthaus/gasthaus-backend-java
  mvn spring-boot:run
  Wait until you see Started GasthausApplication in logs.

  Terminal 3: FastAPI AI Service (port 8000)
  cd ~/Gasthaus/gasthaus-ai
  source venv/bin/activate
  uvicorn app:app --reload --port 8000

  Terminal 4: Next.js Frontend (port 3000)
  cd ~/Gasthaus/gasthaus-dashboard
  npm run dev

  Verify all 4 are up:
  curl -s http://localhost:8080/api/menu/categories | head -c 100
  curl -s http://localhost:8000/health 2>/dev/null || curl -s http://localhost:8000/
  curl -s http://localhost:3000/

  ---
  Phase 1 — Auth Testing

  Open http://localhost:3000 in browser.

  Test 1.1 — Unauthenticated redirect
  - Visit http://localhost:3000/dashboard → should redirect to /login
  - Visit http://localhost:3000/orders → should redirect to /login
  - Visit http://localhost:3000/kitchen → should redirect to /login

  Test 1.2 — Login form validation
  - Submit empty form → zod errors appear on both fields
  - Enter invalid email (e.g. abc) → email error
  - Enter valid email but password < 6 chars → password error

  Test 1.3 — Login with wrong credentials
  - Email: wrong@test.com, Password: wrongpass → red error banner shows

  Test 1.4 — Login as MANAGER
  Email: (use a manager account you seeded)
  ▎ If no accounts exist yet, create one via API first:
  curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/register \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"name":"Admin Manager","email":"manager@test.com","password":"pass123","role":"MANAGER"}'
  - Login → should land on /dashboard
  - Check browser localStorage: gasthaus_token and gasthaus_user keys exist
  - Header shows correct name + avatar initials
  - Sidebar shows all 7 nav items

  Test 1.5 — Login as KITCHEN role
  curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/register \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"name":"Kitchen Staff","email":"kitchen@test.com","password":"pass123","role":"KITCHEN"}'
  - Login as kitchen user → should redirect to /kitchen, NOT /dashboard

  Test 1.6 — Login as WAITER
  curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/register \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"name":"Waiter One","email":"waiter@test.com","password":"pass123","role":"WAITER"}'
  - Login as waiter → should land on /dashboard

  Test 1.7 — Logout / session expiry
  - While logged in, manually delete gasthaus_token from DevTools → Application → Local Storage
  - Refresh page → redirects to /login

  ---
  Phase 2 — Dashboard Page

  Login as MANAGER. Go to /dashboard.

  Test 2.1 — Seed some data first
  # Get manager token
  TOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/login \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"email":"manager@test.com","password":"pass123"}' | python3 -c "import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin)['token'])")

  echo "Token: $TOKEN"

  # Create tables
  for i in 1 2 3 4 5; do
    curl -s -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/tables \
      -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
      -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
      -d "{\"tableNumber\": $i}"
  done

  # Create menu category
  CAT=$(curl -s -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/menu/categories \
    -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"name":"Mains","icon":"🍽️ "}')
  CAT_ID=$(echo $CAT | python3 -c "import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin)['id'])")

  # Create a menu item (no image)
  ITEM=$(curl -s -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/menu/items \
    -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
    -F "name=Beef Burger" \
    -F "description=Juicy beef patty" \
    -F "price=850" \
    -F "categoryId=$CAT_ID")
  echo $ITEM

  Test 2.2 — Stat cards
  - Register a customer and place a couple orders (see Phase 5 setup)
  - Total Orders Today: count matches orders placed today
  - Revenue Today: sum of totalAmount
  - Active Tables: X/Y format, denominator = total tables created
  - Pending Orders: count of PENDING + CONFIRMED status orders

  Test 2.3 — Live Orders panel
  - Shows last 6 orders newest-first
  - Each row has: table badge, customer name, items summary, amount, status pill

  Test 2.4 — Tables mini-map
  - Grid shows all tables
  - Free tables: gray/zinc appearance
  - Occupied tables: amber appearance

  ---
  Phase 3 — Orders Kanban

  Go to /orders.

  Test 3.1 — Kanban columns visible
  - 5 columns: PENDING → CONFIRMED → PREPARING → READY → SERVED
  - Horizontal scroll works if many orders

  Test 3.2 — Place test orders first
  # Register customer
  curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/register \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"name":"Test Customer","email":"customer@test.com","password":"pass123","role":"CUSTOMER"}'

  CUST_TOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/login \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"email":"customer@test.com","password":"pass123"}' | python3 -c "import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin)['token'])")

  # Get item ID
  ITEM_ID=$(curl -s http://localhost:8080/api/menu/items | python3 -c "import sys,json; items=json.load(sys.stdin); print(items[0]['id'])")

  # Place order (table 1)
  TABLE_ID=$(curl -s -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" http://localhost:8080/api/tables | python3 -c "import sys,json; t=json.load(sys.stdin); print(t[0]['id'])")

  curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/orders \
    -H "Authorization: Bearer $CUST_TOKEN" \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d "{\"tableId\":\"$TABLE_ID\",\"items\":[{\"menuItemId\":\"$ITEM_ID\",\"quantity\":2}]}"

  Test 3.3 — Move order through Kanban
  1. Order appears in PENDING column
  2. Click Confirm → card moves to CONFIRMED column (purple left border appears)
  3. Click Prep → card moves to PREPARING column
  4. Click Ready → card moves to READY column (green border)
  5. Click Serve → card moves to SERVED (dimmed)

  Test 3.4 — Search filter
  - Type customer name in search → only matching orders show
  - Type table number → filters by table

  Test 3.5 — Period toggle
  - "Today" vs "This Week" changes which orders appear

  Test 3.6 — Refresh button
  - Click refresh → icon spins, then data refreshes

  ---
  Phase 4 — Kitchen Display

  Open a second browser window (or incognito) and log in as kitchen@test.com.

  Test 4.1 — Full-screen dark layout
  - /kitchen — NO sidebar, NO header
  - Full-screen dark background (#111111)
  - Header bar: GASTHAUS brand, live clock ticking, date

  Test 4.2 — Order cards
  - CONFIRMED orders appear with amber border labeled "new"
  - Click "Start Preparing" → card border turns blue
  - Wait 15+ minutes (or manually check the overdue logic) → card border turns red + pulsing
  - Click "Mark Ready" → card border turns green, button shows "Collected ✓" (disabled)

  Test 4.3 — Real-time updates (two windows open)
  - With /orders open in Window 1 (manager) and /kitchen open in Window 2 (kitchen)
  - In Window 1, confirm a pending order
  - Window 2 kitchen display should update without refresh (STOMP WebSocket)
  - In Window 2, mark an order as READY
  - Window 1 orders board should update without refresh

  Test 4.4 — Header counts
  - Active count = CONFIRMED + PREPARING orders
  - Ready count = READY orders

  ---
  Phase 5 — Menu Management

  Go to /menu (as MANAGER).

  Test 5.1 — Category sidebar
  - "All Items" button shows all items
  - Category buttons show item counts
  - Clicking a category filters the grid

  Test 5.2 — Add category
  - Click "Add Category" → input appears
  - Type name, press Enter → category created, appears in sidebar
  - Press Escape → input cancels

  Test 5.3 — Delete category
  - Hover a category → (×) delete button appears
  - Click × → category deleted (if empty; test with items should show error or cascade)

  Test 5.4 — Menu item grid
  - 3-column grid with item cards
  - Available items: full color
  - Unavailable items: opacity-60 + grayscale image

  Test 5.5 — Availability toggle
  - Click toggle on a card → PATCH /menu/items/:id/toggle
  - Card immediately reflects new state (React Query invalidation)

  Test 5.6 — Edit item
  - Click a card → right panel opens with pre-filled form
  - Amber ring appears on selected card
  - Change name/price → Save → item updates in grid
  - Click "Discard" → panel closes, no changes

  Test 5.7 — Delete item
  - In edit panel → click "Remove from Menu" → confirm dialog appears
  - Confirm → item disappears from grid

  Test 5.8 — Add item with image upload
  - Click "Add Item" button → panel opens in create mode
  - Fill in name, price, select category
  - Upload an image (JPG/PNG) → preview shows
  - Save → item appears in grid with image (Cloudinary upload via backend)
  ▎ Note: requires Cloudinary credentials in backend env — if not set, test without image first

  ---
  Phase 6 — Tables Floor Plan

  Go to /tables (as MANAGER or WAITER).

  Test 6.1 — Layout
  - Left panel: stats bar (Total, Occupied, Available) + floor plan dot-grid
  - Right panel: detail panel (shows placeholder text when nothing selected)

  Test 6.2 — Add table
  - Click "Add Table" or the add button → input form appears above floor plan
  - Enter table number (e.g. 6) → press Enter → new tile appears on floor plan
  - Press Escape → cancels

  Test 6.3 — Table tiles
  - Available tables: dashed border, green dot
  - Occupied tables: solid border, customer + order info, red bottom bar
  - Click any tile → detail panel populates on right

  Test 6.4 — Detail panel
  - Shows table number prominently
  - Available table: shows "Available" badge + "Mark as Occupied" button
  - Occupied table: shows customer name, seated duration (counting up live), order amount, status pill

  Test 6.5 — Toggle occupancy
  - Click "Mark as Occupied" / "Mark as Available" → PATCH /tables/:id/toggle
  - Tile appearance updates immediately

  Test 6.6 — Delete table
  - Select a table → "Delete Table" button → confirm dialog
  - Confirm → table removed from floor plan

  ---
  Phase 7 — Reviews

  First, add reviews via API (reviews require CUSTOMER role):
  ORDER_ID=$(curl -s -H "Authorization: Bearer $CUST_TOKEN" http://localhost:8080/api/orders/my | python3 -c "import sys,json; orders=json.load(sys.stdin); print(orders[0]['id'])")

  curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/reviews \
    -H "Authorization: Bearer $CUST_TOKEN" \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d "{\"menuItemId\":\"$ITEM_ID\",\"orderId\":\"$ORDER_ID\",\"rating\":4,\"comment\":\"Great burger!\"}"

  # Add a negative review too
  curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/reviews \
    -H "Authorization: Bearer $CUST_TOKEN" \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d "{\"menuItemId\":\"$ITEM_ID\",\"orderId\":\"$ORDER_ID\",\"rating\":2,\"comment\":\"Too salty\"}"

  Go to /reviews (as MANAGER).

  Test 7.1 — Review cards
  - Each card: customer initials avatar (deterministic color), item name badge, star row, comment, time ago
  - Low-rated cards (≤2★): red left border accent

  Test 7.2 — Stats sidebar
  - Average rating shown with one decimal
  - Star distribution bars (5★ to 1★) with widths proportional to count
  - Sentiment pills: Positive / Neutral / Negative counts
  - If negative reviews exist: "Quick Insight" box appears

  Test 7.3 — Filters
  - Item dropdown → filters by menu item
  - Star dropdown → filter by rating (e.g. show only 2★)
  - Date range → Last 7 Days / Last 30 Days / All Time
  - Sort → Latest First / Oldest First

